    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 1,
      "versionNonce": 7450455015,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "text-1d9124d63f30",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 1964.442438408308,
      "y": 690.5096582662733,
      "strokeColor": "#57534E",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 407.0751953125,
      "height": 276.25,
      "seed": 617199,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Controller Boundary Pitfall\nA common bad design is making the CNC (Computer Numerical\nControl) controller responsible for things it can only request, not\nguarantee. In a DIY (Do-It-Yourself) machine, this happens when an E-\nstop (Emergency Stop), spindle permissive, or hard limit is treated as\njust another FluidNC input. The firmware may stop sending steps, but\nif the controller crashes, USB (Universal Serial Bus) drops, an output\ntransistor fails, or a relay is wired normally-open in the wrong place,\nthe drive enable or spindle run signal can remain in an unsafe state.\n\nPrevent this by keeping the controller's job focused on machine state\nand coordinated motion. Let it read limits, homes, drive alarms,\nprobes, and process faults for diagnosis and orderly stops, but do not\nmake it the only authority over hazardous energy. Use fail-safe input\nwiring, define clear alarm and reset states, bring fault signals back into\nthe controller, and use external safety hardware where stopping must\nstill work when the controller is wrong.",
      "fontSize": 13,
      "fontFamily": 2,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 16.25,
      "containerId": "node-1d9124d63f30",
      "originalText": "Controller Boundary Pitfall\nA common bad design is making the CNC (Computer Numerical Control) controller responsible for things it can only request, not guarantee. In a DIY (Do-It-Yourself) machine, this happens when an E-stop (Emergency Stop), spindle permissive, or hard limit is treated as just another FluidNC input. The firmware may stop sending steps, but if the controller crashes, USB (Universal Serial Bus) drops, an output transistor fails, or a relay is wired normally-open in the wrong place, the drive enable or spindle run signal can remain in an unsafe state.\n\nPrevent this by keeping the controller's job focused on machine state and coordinated motion. Let it read limits, homes, drive alarms, probes, and process faults for diagnosis and orderly stops, but do not make it the only authority over hazardous energy. Use fail-safe input wiring, define clear alarm and reset states, bring fault signals back into the controller, and use external safety hardware where stopping must still work when the controller is wrong.",
      "lineHeight": 1.25,
      "autoResize": true,
      "customData": {
        "node_id": "controller-boundary-pitfall"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "rectangle",
