    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 1,
      "versionNonce": 1261361421,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "text-e3078bf90fd5",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 2433.765985669867,
      "y": 886.2866980936625,
      "strokeColor": "#57534E",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 413.5751953125,
      "height": 276.25,
      "seed": 94846,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Drive Boundary Pitfall\nBad drive boundaries show up when the controller treats a drive as a\nsilent pulse amplifier. A closed-loop stepper drive may detect following\nerror, encoder loss, overcurrent, or overheating, but if its alarm output is\nnot wired into the controller or safety chain, the rest of the machine can\ncontinue as if the axis still exists. On a dual-Y router, one Y drive\nfaulting while the other side keeps driving can rack the gantry, twist the\nframe, or ruin a fixture before the operator understands the fault.\n\nPrevent this by wiring every drive's alarm, ready, and enable behavior\ndeliberately. Confirm voltage levels, polarity, pullups, step timing, enable\ntiming, and what the drive does after a fault. For coordinated axes, test\none-axis fault cases during commissioning and make the intended stop\nbehavior explicit. Also separate ordinary drive enable from safety-rated\nfunctions: a normal enable input may be useful for control, but STO\n(Safe Torque Off) or a rated safety device is the boundary for\nhazardous torque removal.",
      "fontSize": 13,
      "fontFamily": 2,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 16.25,
      "containerId": "node-e3078bf90fd5",
      "originalText": "Drive Boundary Pitfall\nBad drive boundaries show up when the controller treats a drive as a silent pulse amplifier. A closed-loop stepper drive may detect following error, encoder loss, overcurrent, or overheating, but if its alarm output is not wired into the controller or safety chain, the rest of the machine can continue as if the axis still exists. On a dual-Y router, one Y drive faulting while the other side keeps driving can rack the gantry, twist the frame, or ruin a fixture before the operator understands the fault.\n\nPrevent this by wiring every drive's alarm, ready, and enable behavior deliberately. Confirm voltage levels, polarity, pullups, step timing, enable timing, and what the drive does after a fault. For coordinated axes, test one-axis fault cases during commissioning and make the intended stop behavior explicit. Also separate ordinary drive enable from safety-rated functions: a normal enable input may be useful for control, but STO (Safe Torque Off) or a rated safety device is the boundary for hazardous torque removal.",
      "lineHeight": 1.25,
      "autoResize": true,
      "customData": {
        "node_id": "drive-boundary-pitfall"
      }
    },
