    {
      "type": "text",
      "version": 1,
      "versionNonce": 6845720144,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "id": "text-ade8c916c239",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "x": 2427.673146873642,
      "y": 1257.6330660192225,
      "strokeColor": "#57534E",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "width": 455.2412109375,
      "height": 325.0,
      "seed": 80650,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Safety Boundary Pitfall\nThe worst boundary mistake is confusing an operational stop with a safety\nfunction. Feed hold, reset, sender disconnect, controller reboot, and a normal\ninput pin can be useful controls, but they are not enough for emergency stop,\nguard doors, process energy, or hazardous stored energy. In real machines\nthis shows up as guard switches hidden in ordinary PLC (Programmable Logic\nController) logic, a VFD (Variable Frequency Drive) fault ignored by the CNC\n(Computer Numerical Control), a brake released by a convenience output, or\nan E-stop (Emergency Stop) that stops axis commands while the spindle,\nplasma arc, coolant pump, or pneumatic actuator can still energize.\n\nPrevent this with a safety path that can act independently of normal control.\nUse normally-closed safety circuits, safety relays or safety PLCs\n(Programmable Logic Controllers) where risk requires them, drive STO (Safe\nTorque Off) or appropriate contactors, feedback contacts for contactor\nmonitoring, and a deliberate reset that cannot automatically restart motion. Test\nthe actual result: press E-stop (Emergency Stop), open guards, fault a drive,\nremove air pressure, and verify which energy sources are removed, which\naxes coast or brake, what the controller reports, and what the operator must do\nbefore restart.",
      "fontSize": 13,
      "fontFamily": 2,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 16.25,
      "containerId": "node-ade8c916c239",
      "originalText": "Safety Boundary Pitfall\nThe worst boundary mistake is confusing an operational stop with a safety function. Feed hold, reset, sender disconnect, controller reboot, and a normal input pin can be useful controls, but they are not enough for emergency stop, guard doors, process energy, or hazardous stored energy. In real machines this shows up as guard switches hidden in ordinary PLC (Programmable Logic Controller) logic, a VFD (Variable Frequency Drive) fault ignored by the CNC (Computer Numerical Control), a brake released by a convenience output, or an E-stop (Emergency Stop) that stops axis commands while the spindle, plasma arc, coolant pump, or pneumatic actuator can still energize.\n\nPrevent this with a safety path that can act independently of normal control. Use normally-closed safety circuits, safety relays or safety PLCs (Programmable Logic Controllers) where risk requires them, drive STO (Safe Torque Off) or appropriate contactors, feedback contacts for contactor monitoring, and a deliberate reset that cannot automatically restart motion. Test the actual result: press E-stop (Emergency Stop), open guards, fault a drive, remove air pressure, and verify which energy sources are removed, which axes coast or brake, what the controller reports, and what the operator must do before restart.",
      "lineHeight": 1.25,
      "autoResize": true,
      "customData": {
        "node_id": "safety-boundary-pitfall"
      }
    },
